segments.text: Do you think that had he stayed, he might have had a winning record anyway?

No, I think he, you see, he had Crow and most of those good players graduated, and I think, oh, I think he's the type of guy that would have won somewhere, somehow or another, but I think he'd have dropped back.
He knew it.
He was smart enough to visualize it.
Winning here consistently wasn't in the books.
Well, then when Myers came in, how did things go then?
Well, it went pretty good.
Jim, like I say now, Jim was a good assistant coach, but he didn't have the charisma for being a head coach.
I think he was a good assistant coach.
had a good background under Red Saunders.
But you see, in football, that's a pretty big task.
And a man has to be able to coach, be a head football coach.
He has to be able to visualize everything about it.
Because our assistant coach over here under Red Saunders, our assistant coach under Bear Bryant is a defensive coach.
That wouldn't make me a head coach, would it?
Do you think Bear knew the whole game well, that he was that much of an expert?
No, but he was smart enough to find out from other people.
Then he hired good people to handle each.
Well, and then he, as far as his defenses were concerned, he never did put up a defense until he conferred with Oklahoma coach Bud Wilkinson and Jim Tatum of Maryland.
Hmm.
See?
You see, when he was here, he didn't pass any.
See, his whole offense has changed since he's been at Alabama.
He didn't like kick field goals either, did he?
No.
He just believed in just blowing in and blowing them out, and that was it.
Three yards and a pile of dust.
He didn't have really anything in his offense at all.
He didn't pass very little.
But he got the job done.
got the job done.
How long did Myers stay here?
Myers stayed here about 54, let's see, Bryant left in 57, 58, 59, 60.
And then Fulberg come in?
Fulberg came in in 61, 62, 63.
Stallings came in 65.
So you became athletic director again when Fulberg came in?
No, when he left.
See, I hired Fulberg.
He coached down here.
He was athletic director also?
Yeah, also.
See, they wouldn't give me the athletic director job.
I don't know why, but I didn't make a difference to me.
It was only just an amount of money, but they didn't.
The only thing that made me feel good about the whole thing is they hired me twice as athletic director.
So I must not have been too bad a guy.
Somebody was foolish and didn't know what they were doing, I don't know.
Well, I think they probably had to admit that your administration had been good, that you'd kept them in the black, so to speak.
Can you think of, during this whole period, any major problems you had, financial, otherwise, or things going pretty good?
No, things went along fairly good, and we always had a surplus.
And after 52 and 53, I finally, all this money that we had went into the fiscal office.
And the fiscal office would take it and loan it out.
And finally, I talked them into buying us some government bonds where we could get a little interest off of it.
But it was our money.
They were administering it, but it was our money.
So I talked them into buying some government bonds which we got the interest off of.
Now, all the money.
It goes in there, I put it on time deposit with the fiscal office, I understand from wallet, and they get earnings from it, you see.
Mm-hmm.
Get interest from it.
Mm-hmm.
Were there any plans made at this time?
Were you making any long-range plans to know that the stadium was expanded into 6667?
Yeah, we finally came in with expansion of the stadium.
When was this?
Was this planned a long time in advance?
Well, no, it was...
It was planned after Stallings got there.
Okay, we'll get to that in a minute then.
I was wondering if you all had any long-range goals?
No, what we were trying to do, you see, at that time, the college itself wasn't expanded.
Yeah, I know.
And as far as our home attendance was concerned, we had a stadium there that sat in a seat about 33.
We used to put seats around it.
34,000 or 5,000 spectators, and we didn't have anything.
in demand.
Very seldom you ever see them.
You always, on football, you'd rather have too little than too many.
Oh, my.
And our attendance in those games were fair, but there again we had these good teams that we got money from, like Michigan, Ohio State, LSU, and teams like that, which kept us in the black.
Mm-hmm.
Hmm.
How far ahead do you schedule games?
Could you tell us a little bit about how you go about scheduling the game?
Well, we usually have an athletic director coaches meeting in January every year at some designated place like New York, Chicago, San Francisco.
Everybody from all the NCAA colleges.
You get to know those fellas.
Really?
You do.
You get to know them pretty well.
And you go up there with your schedule in hand and
talk to those people.
I say, I scheduled Army twice, because we never had scheduled them.
Had never played them.
Never played them, and that was one of the dreams of Earl Rudder, to play Army.
But I don't think he lived to see it.
No, he didn't.
And you go up there and you talk to them, just like a convention, and you get with them.
They have the athletic director's meetings, and you get with them, and you bring your schedule, and
Ask them if they'd like to play you.
You just kind of go around and buttonhole them then.
That's right.
And then you write to them during the year and send them your schedule and ask them if they'd be here.
It seems like we go to play these big teams.
Is it for some reason that at least we never seem to have any problems scheduling large teams.
Do they like to play in them on their home turf?
Yes.
Were we considered an easy mark or something?
Well, coaches are a little more what they call non-conference games.
They're a little bit more reluctant to play a team if they think they can beat.
I'll put it that way.
See, we never have.
We've played Michigan two or three times.
Ohio State at least twice.
Twice.
Never have beaten them.
Played USC, LSU.
I think I talked to Marvin the other day, and they've got Illinois coming in here next year.
Well, Illinois used to be a powerhouse.
I don't think they are now.
And then we've got Ole Miss coming in.
Well, Clemson used to be a powerhouse years and years ago.
They're not anymore.
They're sort of a set-up team.
And I don't know anything about the other Kansas that we're going to play or Washington.
Eight years ago, Washington was good.
And, of course, Jim Owens coached in Washington three, four, five years ago.
They had a great team.
Mm-hmm.
And Kansas had a good team last year, but they lost their quarterback.
They'll be just a so-so team.
We ought to be able to win two out of our three non-conference games, I think.
I think right now we're in the best position as far as material-wise and depth that we've been in since I can remember.
Well, we might go on now and talk about, say, was there anything that happened during the Myers era that was interesting?
No, nothing more.
Jim
Jim was, I liked Jim, and we got along fine.
And I thought he did a fairly good job.
Must be a fairly decent coach.
He's still at Dallas.
Yeah, well, he's an assistant coach.
And he's, well, he's obviously a specialist in one phase of the game.
He didn't know anything just between us boys.
He didn't know anything about offense or defense either.
what I could see.
I mean, I've had experience, 15 years of experience, of running the whole thing in high school and some part of colleges.
But you can very easily, Jim, he was a good line coach.
As far as the technical part of offense and defense, I don't think he was superb.
He had to depend upon his assistants.
And then Fulberg came in.
What'd you think of Fulberg?
This is the first coach I remember here.
Well, Fulberg, you know, he had been here.
I had hired him as a, there you go again, you see.
I had hired Fulberg in 52 as an end coach.
He stayed here one or two years, and then went to Florida.
Then when he came in one of them, he hired me again, see.
Of course, he made him athletic director again, see.
I went through that experience with all these coaches.
Well, Fulberg was all right there again.
I think Fulberg made a good athletic director.
He did stay on one year, didn't he?
Well, he stayed on from December to July.
He was progressive and he had good ideas and everything, but I don't think he was a head coach.
I don't think he had the... A guy to be a head coach, that's his only job.
That's a big job.

be what you might call dedicated to that one particular job and that's a 24-hour day job he's got he's called upon for so many other things outside of in other words he's a public relation man and and the head coach and his biggest deal is to hire people that know more than he does at particular positions get what i'm talking about the specialists
Unless he does, that's, I think, one of the main reasons why Darrell Waltz has been so successful.
He hasn't changed his coaches.
And he's had people under him that knew what they were doing, and he kept them and paid them.
I think royally.
Of course, you might not agree with being an Aggie, but I don't know.
I don't see how you can argue with success, though.
Nothing succeeds like success.
Yeah.
You know, watching Fulberg, I always thought he built some fairly decent defensive teams.
Well, there again, it was the assistants.
Fulberg, he'd sit up in the stands a lot.
I don't think Fulberg was actually
interested in head coaching.
He was more interested in going ahead and being an athletic director.
I see.
He didn't want that routine and that work that was attached to it.
Being a head coach is a 12-month-a-year job.
That's right.
But he was all right.
Like I say again, there you are.
I went through it with good friends and everything.
But, of course, he was let go.
I think Stallings had a lot to do with that.
Who, how did we get Gene Stallings?
How did?
Well, two directors went out and hired him.
I shouldn't say that over the tape.
He was recommended by Barry Bryant.
That's a good recommendation.
That's a good one.
You can't go, you can't beat that.
Yeah.
And he was recommended to two of the board's directors.
And of course, being a young coach and having a fine background and being the first assistant at Alabama,
and being an A&M player and a former student and everything, it looked like he was, you know, he was the right man.
And of course he came in here and things, I remember that it was an exciting time.
Things changed around, it seemed.
Oh yeah, he changed everything around.
And Gene was a personal friend of mine.
I like him fine.
He's got lots on the ball.
But some people are growing some swell.
Hellenfeld told me he thought that Gene Stallings knew more about football than anybody he'd ever met.
Well, I disagree with him.
Why should Hellenfeld, the contractor... Well, you know, everybody has an opinion, and sometimes you think you're an expert on everything.
Well, I disagree with him.
Now, don't get me wrong, I think he's a knowledgeable man, but I don't think he knew more about football than anybody.
Because that's a hard thing to decide.
Did he tell you that, Sidney?
Well, he got very mad about it when that started.
Of course, Mr. Peterson.
I got that impression.
You talked to Peterson?
No, I talked to Mr. Heldenfeld, and I got the impression that he really liked Gene Stallings, and that that was a subject I wasn't to get into with him.
That was a very sore spot, so I didn't pursue it any further.
Gene would have been here today, and I told him.
I was athletic director then, and I told him.
I did everything in the world to help Gene.
But his biggest problem was that he couldn't get along with the administration.
I wasn't aware of that.
Huh?
I wasn't aware of that.
I thought maybe he had more trouble with his boys than he did.
No.
I shouldn't say this, because if he ever reads it, he'll be on me.
But instead, if problems would come up, I would recommend to the council what to do.
we wanted to be done as athletic director.
Then the council would recommend to the president.
The president would OK it.
In two or three days, the president would call me and say, we're not going to do it that way.
And the reason for it was that Gene would go around the president and go to two board members.
And the board members would bring pressure on the president.
I mean, Rutter didn't like that.
No, sir.
I don't imagine he did, no.
He'd come to me, and I coached Rutter, and he'd come to me and say, Bones, what were you going to do about that boy down there?
I said, don't ask me.
I said, you can't do anything with him.
You think maybe this, because Stallings was a reasonably young man, he still had something to learn?
He sure did.
He was a good Christian boy and everything, but he just running roughshod over everybody.
And you can't run a rough shot over the athletic council and the president of the institution.
You're not going to run a rough shot over Earl Rudd.
Of course, he was let...
He was...
The Stallings, he was let go in... Seventy... That's after Earl's death.
Yeah, he was let go in... Seventy-two.
That was his biggest problem.
And Earl didn't like it.
I'm going to tell you something that President Williams told me.
He told me that when Earl, when he came here as president of this institution, and Stallings went to him and told him and said, Mr. Williams, I'm glad that you're here, but you're not my boss.
Now, the president told me that with his own mouth.
Now, what would you do?
That goes right back to the thing I said.
He couldn't get along with administrations.
They called me out there after I retired.
Mr. Butler, D. Butler was the chairman of the Athletic Council.
He said, what is the duties of the Athletic Council?
I said, you can just look in the rule book there at Southwest Conference.
You can see what the rules are.

I said, they have direct supervision over all activities of the athletic department, including the budgetary and all other rules and regulations that are set up that are passed on to the president for approval.
He called me out.
He didn't want to know what the athletic council had to do with him.
And I said, well, he's there, your boss.
He just laughed at me and told me, hey, don't know.
I said, I'm a dean.
I'm not responsible to anybody around me except for the board.
Now, that was the reason.
I don't know whether that's going on tape.
That's up to you.
I wouldn't put that on tape.
But that's a true story.
That's interesting.
I'm glad to know that.
And that's the reason Chris Gronman left here.
He's just one of the reasons they wouldn't take him off the council.
And he just decided he had to.
And, oh, yeah, fine fellow.
Great personality, and I'm still a good friend of his.
Why should a fellow just, like I said a while ago, some people grow and some swell?
He'd still be at A&M.
The Helen fellow didn't know that.
Maybe that's a little bit of immaturity on his part, something he'll outgrow.
Well, I imagine he's not telling the Lankers what to do.
Oh, I don't imagine so.
He wouldn't tell Brian what to do.
I wouldn't put that in the script, so if you... That's between me and you.
That ought to be... Do you know anything about Ballard's hiring, the selection?
The president hired him.
President Williams hired him?
He did all the searching himself?
Yeah.
He got Bud Wilkinson...
to be, what do you mean, consultant?
Yeah, that's a good enough term.
Consultant.
To go out and recommend somebody to him.
And of course he picked a good man to be.
That's right.
Was Bud Wilkerson ever interviewed for a job here?
No, I don't think so.
Of course he had thumbs down on it because he had a bird nest on the ground up in Oklahoma.
And he's got a good one in television, too.
That's right.
But Dr. Williams, I remember hearing him say that he was going to pick the coach this time.
That's interesting.
I know there were a lot of rumors flying then.
I was in the service, and there was a rumor in the paper they'd offered Charlie McClendon down there a million dollars.
Well, that's right.
Now, there again, the board got into that.
Now, this is his hearsay now.
I'm going to tell you this story.
retired now, he had coached Charlie McKinnon in some junior high school at some small college in Arkansas, and he was pretty close to Charlie.
And I understand that he and two of the board members flew out.
Now this is hearsay.
Hearsay, yeah.
There's no factual evidence on this.
They flew out to California to make this offer to Charlie, and Charlie wouldn't accept it because he had a bowl game coming up.
That is interesting.
So I think Emery was the choice of the administration.
Have you had a chance to watch any of his performances?
Do you think he's going to make a pretty good coach?
I think Emery's a very- Seems personable.
Very personable person, but I'm very on the farm 100%.
I belong to the Aggie Club and the Century Club, and I support everything at A&M.
And the quarterback club, I do my share.
There again, I'm just telling you this, he better have a scoreboard in his face.
Oh, I think, and he may be foolish.
I hope Emory stays here for 100 years, because I like him.
I'm for him 100%.
But if he comes up next year with a fourth season, some of these book members will be after him.
You see, a board member, he's succeeded in his profession.
He thinks he's a success.
And he can't tolerate failure.
Yes, I've run into that.
I know exactly what you mean.
He can't tolerate failure.
Well, maybe then the board has become too ingrown.
In other words, we've got too many Aggies on the board.
I think that Mr. Emory, like I said, I hope he stays there forever.
And I think he's doing a good job.
And he's been given everything possible to do it with.
I mean, I can't say we didn't give him this or gave him that.
But there's still some board members on there that will not tolerate defeat.
Oh, well, I'm well aware of people.
I can name them to you, but I'm not going to do it.
Well, that's maybe how they became successful, and that's the way they are, that they...
They drive themselves and they drive everybody else like they drive themselves.
But when you get success, it's not that you have been successful.
They get what they call smart.
It's not altogether your brains or your skill or anything, but anybody that's made success in the world, he's had somebody to help him.
I don't care who you are.
Even the President of the United States, he's had to
with thousands of people helping him.
And you can't succeed without the help of other people.
And like I said before, you've got to be at the right place at the right time and the right people pulling for you, even in your job.
You ought to take over Lindsay's job one of these days.
No, I'm in the library.
You're out of that, aren't you?
We're just trying to be everybody's friend and find out what we can.
Did you take journalism here?
No, no, I'm a historian.
Oh, well, maybe you can help me with my history.
Well, if I can, I'd be glad to.
You know Charles Crawford?
Do you know Professor Crawford?
Gosh, well, he's in the Rotary Club with me.
Well, Charlie Crawford is up there in the archives, and that's where he writes.
He's writing the history of the engineering department.
And he's been up there for years.
Of course, mine will be a little bit different.
Because mine will be sort of a background on my family, which I want to put in my life, which has been interesting.
Do you think that retiring in 67 as you went out with the Southwest Conference Championship, that was a good time to retire, to go out on a good note there?
Yes, it was.
I hadn't quite reached 65 when Mr. Ruddard told me I could stay here as long as I wanted to.
But I'll be frank with you, I had other things I wanted to do.
And I was in a position to where I didn't have to have a job.
That's a good position to be in.
And secondly, although Gene was a very personal friend of mine and everything, I just got fed up with it.
I mean, just being knocked around and one thing or another.
I wasn't proud, but I had pride.
Certainly.
And I was positioned where I didn't have to.
I'm not a rich man, but I'm comfortably fixed.
I am.
I am.
A couple little dumb questions.
They may not mean anything, but I've always wondered about who chooses the uniforms that they wear.
We change uniforms every few years, and I've always wondered what.
Coaches.
Every coach that comes in here just wipes out all equipment, and they start in again with their own design.
Because it seemed like when Gene Stallings came back, we went back to sort of the Bear Bryant style again.
Yeah, the prettiest uniforms I ever had here was when I came here as a freshman.
They hadn't.

gray uniform with maroon stripes around it, and blended in with a, I like that, that was mine, but Harris changed it, Myers changed it, Fulberg, see, Fulberg changed it, and Emory changed it, Gene's changed it.
See, I've been here under every coach since Bible.
Except Norton, I could have been here under him, so I got a pretty good surveillance of different coaches.
I just wondered that.
It seemed like every time we got a new coach, here came new uniforms and everything.
That's right.
Coaches do that.
And what significance it has to the winning of the ball games, I don't know.
Of course, our colors are maroon and white, and I've always thought that just plain uniforms, a maroon jersey with white numbers, with white pants, with
It was very conservative and very pretty.
But when you start putting in all this other stuff, that's high school stuff.
Yeah, I noticed.
Now we go to the stripes down the shoulders.
I just, I don't know.
It's a coach's prerogative.
And change from, say, the maroon helmets to the white helmets now.
I'd always wondered about that.
Well, you must know my friend out there.
What's his name?
A historian.
He's a dean now.
What's his name?
A young fella.
He used to be a historian.
Haskell Monroe.
Yeah, Haskell.
Yes, I do.
Is he still studying history?
He's a busy man.
He's a vice president of the university now.
He used to be a swiner.
I used to know him for years.
He's a good history pro.
He's a very, very, a man of a lot of abilities, I imagine.
Yeah.
He teaches, I think, one history course now, and the rest of his time is in Old South, I believe.
And I think most of his time is now wound up in administration.
He works under Dr. Calhoun.
They say now that Calhoun runs the school.
Is that right?
The man of great influence, let's say.
He has a very responsible job.
You haven't got the thing on.
Yeah, I've got it on.
I can turn it off.
There.
